TY  - JOUR
AU  - Pozsonyi, E.
AU  - Lengyelné Molnár, T.
AU  - Racsko, R.
TI  - To ban or not to ban–domestic and international experiences of restricting mobile phone ban use in schools
PY  - 2025
JO  - Educational Media International
DO  - 10.1080/09523987.2025.2588529
AB  - Perspectives on the use of telecommunication devices in educational institutions vary internationally. France implemented restrictions in 2017, followed by China in 2018 and Canada in 2019, with several other countries - including Denmark, Sweden, and England - subsequently adopting similar measures. Evidence suggests that banning mobile phones in schools produces mixed outcomes regarding students’ academic achievement, mental well-being, and exposure to cyberbullying. In Hungary, such regulation took effect on 1 September 2024 under Government Decree No. 245/2024 (VIII. 8.), which designates telecommunication devices as prohibited or restricted items within schools. The primary rationale is that mobile phone use distracts students from learning and facilitates cyberbullying. The decree applies to mobile phones, tablets, laptops, and smartwatches, while allowing occasional use with explicit permission from a teacher or principal, provided the purpose and duration are clearly defined. This study presents findings from a quantitative survey conducted among secondary school teachers regarding the local implementation of these restrictions and their perceived impact on classroom activities and break-time interactions. Drawing on the responses of 1,198 teachers, the paper offers a summary of the first year’s experiences following the enforcement of the regulation. © 2025 International Council for Educational Media.
ER  -

TY  - JOUR
AU  - Frolovičeva, V.
AU  - Daniela, L.
TI  - The Discrepancy Between Teachers’ Perceptions and Students’ Experience Regarding the Teachers’ Watchfulness in Technology-Enriched Classrooms
PY  - 2025
JO  - Technology, Knowledge and Learning
DO  - 10.1007/s10758-025-09887-x
AB  - This study highlights educators’ challenges in orchestrating student interactions within technology-rich environments. Specifically, it investigates teachers’ perceptions and their students’ experiences in technology-enriched classrooms, focusing on internal school policies, provided ICT infrastructure, and teacher-student engagement with digital devices during lessons. A quantitative case study framework was employed for data collection. Data was gathered from two schools using online questionnaires distributed to secondary school teachers and students, resulting in 307 respondents. The findings reveal a significant gap between school policies and the actual use of digital devices in classrooms, indicating that despite restrictions on mobile phone usage and provided infrastructure, students frequently use their smartphones for educational purposes. Statistical analyses using SPSS revealed notable differences in teachers’ perceptions and students’ experiences using digital devices in a classroom. The results emphasize the need for schools to revise internal regulations and for educators to adopt more effective strategies to foster an equitable and focused technology-enhanced learning environment. © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer Nature B.V. 2025.
